julian assange [SEP] personal life [SEP] what is interesting about assange 's personal life ? [SEP] born in townsville , queensland , to christine ann hawkins ( b. 1951 ) , a visual artist , and john shipton , an anti - war activist and builder . the couple had separated before assange was born . [SEP] did he ever received formal education ? [SEP] he attended many schools , including goolmangar primary school in new south wales ( 1979 - 1983 ) and townsville state high school , as well as being schooled at home . [SEP] did he go to college ?
julian assange [SEP] personal life [SEP] what is interesting about assange 's personal life ? [SEP] born in townsville , queensland , to christine ann hawkins ( b. 1951 ) , a visual artist , and john shipton , an anti - war activist and builder . the couple had separated before assange was born . [SEP] did he ever received formal education ? [SEP] he attended many schools , including goolmangar primary school in new south wales ( 1979 - 1983 ) and townsville state high school , as well as being schooled at home . [SEP] did he go to college ? [SEP] he studied programming , mathematics , and physics at central queensland university ( 1994 ) and the university of melbourne ( 2003 - 2006 ) , but did not complete a degree . [SEP] what did he do after college , why did nt he get the degree ?

melungeon [SEP] definition [SEP] what is this about [SEP] the ancestry and identity of melungeons has been a highly controversial subject . [SEP] what do the others say [SEP] secondary sources disagree as to their ethnic , linguistic , cultural , and geographic origins and identity , as they are of mixed racial ancestry . [SEP] what could be be said [SEP] they might accurately be described as a loose collection of families of diverse origins who migrated , settled near each other , and intermarried , [SEP] who was this about [SEP] mostly in hancock and hawkins counties in tennessee , nearby areas of kentucky , and in lee county , virginia . [SEP] what where the ancetors about [SEP] their ancestors can usually be traced back to colonial virginia and the carolinas . [SEP] what was the marriage about [SEP] they were largely endogamous , marrying primarily within their community until about 1900 . [SEP] what did this cause [SEP] melungeons have been defined as having multiracial ancestry . they did not exhibit characteristics that could be classified as those of a single racial phenotype . [SEP] what did this change [SEP] appalachian families traditionally regarded as melungeon are generally european american in appearance , often ( though not always ) with dark hair and eyes , and a swarthy or olive complexion . carlos santana [SEP] amplifiers [SEP] what is amplifiers ? [SEP] carlos santana 's distinctive guitar tone is produced by prs santana signature guitars plugged into multiple amplifiers . [SEP] what do the amplifiers do for carlos santana ? [SEP] santana compares the tonal qualities of each amplifier to that of a singer producing head / nasal tones , chest tones , and belly tones . [SEP] are there any songs that he uses his amplifiers on ?
carlos santana [SEP] amplifiers [SEP] what is amplifiers ? [SEP] carlos santana 's distinctive guitar tone is produced by prs santana signature guitars plugged into multiple amplifiers . [SEP] what do the amplifiers do for carlos santana ? [SEP] santana compares the tonal qualities of each amplifier to that of a singer producing head / nasal tones , chest tones , and belly tones . [SEP] are there any songs that he uses his amplifiers on ? [SEP] used at the woodstock concert as well as during recording santana 's debut album . [SEP] why are the amplifiers important ?

[SEP] from world war i through to the end of world war ii , turkana actively participated in the wars as allies of britain against invading italy . [SEP] did turkana have a significant impact on the wars ? [SEP] turkana was used as the launching pad for the war against invading italian forces leading to the liberation of abyssinia . [SEP] what happened with turkana after the liberation of abyssinia ?

[SEP] from world war i through to the end of world war ii , turkana actively participated in the wars as allies of britain against invading italy . [SEP] did turkana have a significant impact on the wars ? [SEP] turkana was used as the launching pad for the war against invading italian forces leading to the liberation of abyssinia . [SEP] what happened with turkana after the liberation of abyssinia ? [SEP] after world war ii , the british led disarmament and pacification campaigns in turkana , leading to massive disruptions and dispossession of turkana pastoralists . [SEP] what sort of religious history does turkana have ?

albert ayler [SEP] artistry [SEP] what was albert 's style ? [SEP] very conventional musical contexts , including children 's songs , march melodies , and gospel hymns . [SEP] what else was different about his artistry ? [SEP] however , ayler 's wild energy and intense improvisations transformed them into something nearly unrecognizable . [SEP] what was his style of music ?
albert ayler [SEP] artistry [SEP] what was albert 's style ? [SEP] ayler routinely showcased his highly untraditional personal saxophone style in very conventional musical contexts , [SEP] what musical contexts ? [SEP] very conventional musical contexts , including children 's songs , march melodies , and gospel hymns . [SEP] what else was different about his artistry ? [SEP] however , ayler 's wild energy and intense improvisations transformed them into something nearly unrecognizable . [SEP] what was his style of music ? [SEP] ayler took a deconstructive approach to his music , which was characteristic of the free jazz era . [SEP] what other things made his music sound different ?
albert ayler [SEP] artistry [SEP] what was albert 's style ? [SEP] ayler routinely showcased his highly untraditional personal saxophone style in very conventional musical contexts , [SEP] what musical contexts ? [SEP] very conventional musical contexts , including children 's songs , march melodies , and gospel hymns . [SEP] what else was different about his artistry ? [SEP] however , ayler 's wild energy and intense improvisations transformed them into something nearly unrecognizable . [SEP] what was his style of music ? [SEP] ayler took a deconstructive approach to his music , which was characteristic of the free jazz era . [SEP] what other things made his music sound different ? [SEP] phil hardy says that ayler " dismantled " melody and harmony in order to more deeply explore " the physical properties " of his saxophone . [SEP] what else was important about his music ?
albert ayler [SEP] artistry [SEP] what was albert 's style ? [SEP] ayler routinely showcased his highly untraditional personal saxophone style in very conventional musical contexts , [SEP] what musical contexts ? [SEP] very conventional musical contexts , including children 's songs , march melodies , and gospel hymns . [SEP] what else was different about his artistry ? [SEP] however , ayler 's wild energy and intense improvisations transformed them into something nearly unrecognizable . [SEP] what was his style of music ? [SEP] ayler took a deconstructive approach to his music , which was characteristic of the free jazz era . [SEP] what other things made his music sound different ? [SEP] phil hardy says that ayler " dismantled " melody and harmony in order to more deeply explore " the physical properties " of his saxophone . [SEP] what else was important about his music ? [SEP] ayler wished to free himself and his bandmates to improvise , relate to one another , and relate to their instruments on a more raw , " primal " level . [SEP] was he similar to any other musicians ?

fred hampton [SEP] legal and political impacts [SEP] was he involved with any court cases [SEP] the families of hampton and clark filed a us$ 47.7 million civil suit against the city , state , and federal governments . [SEP] what was the result of that suit ? [SEP] more than a decade after the case had been filed , the suit was finally settled for $ 1.85 million . [SEP] why did it take over a decade ?
fred hampton [SEP] legal and political impacts [SEP] was he involved with any court cases [SEP] the families of hampton and clark filed a us$ 47.7 million civil suit against the city , state , and federal governments . [SEP] what was the result of that suit ? [SEP] more than a decade after the case had been filed , the suit was finally settled for $ 1.85 million . [SEP] why did it take over a decade ? [SEP] judge perry dismissed the case . the plaintiffs appealed and the u.s. court of appeals for the seventh circuit reversed , ordering the case to be retried . [SEP] what political impacts did he have ?
fred hampton [SEP] legal and political impacts [SEP] was he involved with any court cases [SEP] the families of hampton and clark filed a us$ 47.7 million civil suit against the city , state , and federal governments . [SEP] what was the result of that suit ? [SEP] more than a decade after the case had been filed , the suit was finally settled for $ 1.85 million . [SEP] why did it take over a decade ? [SEP] judge perry dismissed the case . the plaintiffs appealed and the u.s. court of appeals for the seventh circuit reversed , ordering the case to be retried . [SEP] what political impacts did he have ? [SEP] empowering the most oppressed sector of chicago 's black community , bringing people into political life through participation in their own freedom fighting organization . [SEP] are there any other interesting aspects about this article ?
fred hampton [SEP] legal and political impacts [SEP] was he involved with any court cases [SEP] the families of hampton and clark filed a us$ 47.7 million civil suit against the city , state , and federal governments . [SEP] what was the result of that suit ? [SEP] more than a decade after the case had been filed , the suit was finally settled for $ 1.85 million . [SEP] why did it take over a decade ? [SEP] judge perry dismissed the case . the plaintiffs appealed and the u.s. court of appeals for the seventh circuit reversed , ordering the case to be retried . [SEP] what political impacts did he have ? [SEP] empowering the most oppressed sector of chicago 's black community , bringing people into political life through participation in their own freedom fighting organization . [SEP] are there any other interesting aspects about this article ? [SEP] commemorating december 4 , 2004 , as " fred hampton day in chicago " . [SEP] why was he given his own day ?
fred hampton [SEP] legal and political impacts [SEP] was he involved with any court cases [SEP] the families of hampton and clark filed a us$ 47.7 million civil suit against the city , state , and federal governments . [SEP] what was the result of that suit ? [SEP] more than a decade after the case had been filed , the suit was finally settled for $ 1.85 million . [SEP] why did it take over a decade ? [SEP] judge perry dismissed the case . the plaintiffs appealed and the u.s. court of appeals for the seventh circuit reversed , ordering the case to be retried . [SEP] what political impacts did he have ? [SEP] empowering the most oppressed sector of chicago 's black community , bringing people into political life through participation in their own freedom fighting organization . [SEP] are there any other interesting aspects about this article ? [SEP] commemorating december 4 , 2004 , as " fred hampton day in chicago " . [SEP] why was he given his own day ? [SEP] he did not regret his collaboration with the nazis because this cooperation had made it possible to rescue numerous nazi victims from execution , or death in extermination camps . [SEP] victorian burlesque , sometimes known as " travesty " or " extravaganza " , was popular in london theatres [SEP] what were some elements of these shows ? [SEP] parody in which a well - known opera , play or ballet was adapted into a broad comic play , usually a musical play , [SEP] were these shows popular with the public ? [SEP] some of the most frequent subjects for burlesque were the plays of shakespeare and grand opera . [SEP] were any performances especially popular ? [SEP] were often one - act pieces running less than an hour and using pastiches and parodies of popular songs , opera arias and other music that the audience would readily recognize . patrice lumumba [SEP] deposition [SEP] what happened with the deposition ? [SEP] lumumba denounced his dismissal over the radio as illegitimate , and in turn labeled kasa - vubu a traitor and declared him deposed . [SEP] did kasa - vubu depose him ? [SEP] on 13 september , the parliament held a joint session between the senate and the assembly . though several members short of a quorum , they voted to grant lumumba emergency powers . [SEP] what happened after this ?
patrice lumumba [SEP] deposition [SEP] what happened with the deposition ? [SEP] lumumba denounced his dismissal over the radio as illegitimate , and in turn labeled kasa - vubu a traitor and declared him deposed . [SEP] did kasa - vubu depose him ? [SEP] still , parliament did not back lumumba 's dismissal of kasa - vubu , creating a constitutional crisis . [SEP] how did they solve this problem ? [SEP] on 13 september , the parliament held a joint session between the senate and the assembly . though several members short of a quorum , they voted to grant lumumba emergency powers . [SEP] what happened after this ? [SEP] on 14 september , a coup d'etat organised by colonel mobutu politically incapacitated both lumumba and kasa - vubu . [SEP] what did lumumba do about this ?

[SEP] the band hired robert fleischman and transitioned to a more popular style , [SEP] why did they change their musical direction ? [SEP] journey 's album sales did not improve and columbia records requested that they change their musical style and add a frontman , with whom keyboardist gregg rolie could share lead vocal duties . [SEP] simon 's characters are typically portrayed as " imperfect , unheroic figures who are at heart decent human beings " , [SEP] does he act as characters ? [SEP] he reproduces speech so " adroitly " that his characters are usually plausible and easy for audiences to identify with and laugh at . [SEP] how does he come up with ideas for his characters ?
neil simon [SEP] characters [SEP] what is a typical character for him ? [SEP] simon 's characters are typically portrayed as " imperfect , unheroic figures who are at heart decent human beings " , [SEP] does he act as characters ? [SEP] he reproduces speech so " adroitly " that his characters are usually plausible and easy for audiences to identify with and laugh at . [SEP] how does he come up with ideas for his characters ? [SEP] before writing , simon tries to create an image of his characters . [SEP] what is a well known character ?
neil simon [SEP] characters [SEP] what is a typical character for him ? [SEP] simon 's characters are typically portrayed as " imperfect , unheroic figures who are at heart decent human beings " , [SEP] does he act as characters ? [SEP] he reproduces speech so " adroitly " that his characters are usually plausible and easy for audiences to identify with and laugh at . [SEP] how does he come up with ideas for his characters ? [SEP] before writing , simon tries to create an image of his characters . [SEP] what is a well known character ? [SEP] many of simon 's most memorable plays are built around two - character scenes , as in segments of california suite and plaza suite . [SEP] what does the public think about his characters ?
neil simon [SEP] characters [SEP] what is a typical character for him ? [SEP] simon 's characters are typically portrayed as " imperfect , unheroic figures who are at heart decent human beings " , [SEP] does he act as characters ? [SEP] he reproduces speech so " adroitly " that his characters are usually plausible and easy for audiences to identify with and laugh at . [SEP] how does he come up with ideas for his characters ? [SEP] before writing , simon tries to create an image of his characters . [SEP] what is a well known character ? [SEP] many of simon 's most memorable plays are built around two - character scenes , as in segments of california suite and plaza suite . [SEP] what does the public think about his characters ? [SEP] simon 's characters often amuse the audience with sparkling " zingers , " believable due to simon 's skill with writing dialogue . [SEP] are there any other qualities the audience enjoys ?
neil simon [SEP] characters [SEP] what is a typical character for him ? [SEP] simon 's characters are typically portrayed as " imperfect , unheroic figures who are at heart decent human beings " , [SEP] does he act as characters ? [SEP] he reproduces speech so " adroitly " that his characters are usually plausible and easy for audiences to identify with and laugh at . [SEP] how does he come up with ideas for his characters ? [SEP] before writing , simon tries to create an image of his characters . [SEP] what is a well known character ? [SEP] namdev and jnanesvar used the marathi language to convey their beliefs rather than using the traditional sanskrit language [SEP] was their reliability in question ? [SEP] " he taught that all can be saved equally , without regard to caste , through devotion ( bhakti ) to vithoba " and that he greatly influenced groups of people who were forbidden [SEP] did he have a large following ? [SEP] he greatly influenced groups of people who were forbidden by the brahmin elite from studying the vedas , such as women and members of the shudra and untouchable communities . [SEP] was he able to make a positive change ?

[SEP] he greatly influenced groups of people who were forbidden by the brahmin elite from studying the vedas , such as women and members of the shudra and untouchable communities . [SEP] for the first time in tennis history , the women 's match was the headline event of the tour ( which also featured male players ) . [SEP] who did lenglen work with ?

richard lewontin [SEP] work in population genetics [SEP] what type of work was richard involved in ? [SEP] both theoretical and experimental population genetics . [SEP] what else did he accomplish ? [SEP] technology . he was the first person to do a computer simulation of the behavior of a single gene locus ( previous simulation work having been of models with multiple loci ) . richard lewontin [SEP] work in population genetics [SEP] what type of work was richard involved in ? [SEP] both theoretical and experimental population genetics . [SEP] what else did he accomplish ? [SEP] technology . he was the first person to do a computer simulation of the behavior of a single gene locus ( previous simulation work having been of models with multiple loci ) . [SEP] what else was he the first to do ? [SEP] he and ken - ichi kojima were the first population geneticists to give the equations for change of haplotype frequencies with interacting natural selection at two loci . [SEP] what resulted from these discoveries ?
richard lewontin [SEP] work in population genetics [SEP] what type of work was richard involved in ? [SEP] both theoretical and experimental population genetics . [SEP] what else did he accomplish ? [SEP] technology . he was the first person to do a computer simulation of the behavior of a single gene locus ( previous simulation work having been of models with multiple loci ) . [SEP] what resulted from these discoveries ? [SEP] the discovery of high levels of molecular variability gave population geneticists ample material to work on , and gave them access to variation at single loci . spice girls [SEP] girl power [SEP] exactly what is meant by the spice girls girl power ? [SEP] the phrase " girl power " put a name to a social phenomenon , but the slogan was met with mixed reactions . [SEP] what mixed reactions did it have ? [SEP] post classical neo - feminist empowerment embraced by the band : that a sensual , feminine appearance and equality between the sexes need not be mutually exclusive . [SEP] what else happened following these mixed reactions ? [SEP] it was not until the emergence of the spice girls in 1996 with " wannabe " , that the concept of " girl power " exploded onto the common consciousness . [SEP] were there a lot of controversy going on at this time ?
spice girls [SEP] girl power [SEP] exactly what is meant by the spice girls girl power ? [SEP] the phrase " girl power " put a name to a social phenomenon , but the slogan was met with mixed reactions . [SEP] what mixed reactions did it have ? [SEP] post classical neo - feminist empowerment embraced by the band : that a sensual , feminine appearance and equality between the sexes need not be mutually exclusive . [SEP] what else happened following these mixed reactions ? [SEP] it was not until the emergence of the spice girls in 1996 with " wannabe " , that the concept of " girl power " exploded onto the common consciousness . [SEP] were there a lot of controversy going on at this time ? [SEP] some critics dismissed it as no more than a shallow marketing tactic , while others took issue with the emphasis on physical appearance , [SEP] did the spice girls go on to be successful regarding their girl power ?
spice girls [SEP] girl power [SEP] exactly what is meant by the spice girls girl power ? [SEP] the phrase " girl power " put a name to a social phenomenon , but the slogan was met with mixed reactions . [SEP] what mixed reactions did it have ? [SEP] post classical neo - feminist empowerment embraced by the band : that a sensual , feminine appearance and equality between the sexes need not be mutually exclusive . [SEP] what else happened following these mixed reactions ? [SEP] it was not until the emergence of the spice girls in 1996 with " wannabe " , that the concept of " girl power " exploded onto the common consciousness . [SEP] were there a lot of controversy going on at this time ? [SEP] some critics dismissed it as no more than a shallow marketing tactic , while others took issue with the emphasis on physical appearance , [SEP] did the spice girls go on to be successful regarding their girl power ? [SEP] the spice girls ' debut single " wannabe " has been hailed as an " iconic girl power anthem " . [SEP] did they have a huge following ?
spice girls [SEP] girl power [SEP] exactly what is meant by the spice girls girl power ? [SEP] the phrase " girl power " put a name to a social phenomenon , but the slogan was met with mixed reactions . [SEP] what mixed reactions did it have ? [SEP] post classical neo - feminist empowerment embraced by the band : that a sensual , feminine appearance and equality between the sexes need not be mutually exclusive . [SEP] what else happened following these mixed reactions ? [SEP] it was not until the emergence of the spice girls in 1996 with " wannabe " , that the concept of " girl power " exploded onto the common consciousness . [SEP] were there a lot of controversy going on at this time ? [SEP] some critics dismissed it as no more than a shallow marketing tactic , while others took issue with the emphasis on physical appearance , [SEP] did the spice girls go on to be successful regarding their girl power ? boy band [SEP] early history [SEP] when was the first boy band ? [SEP] the earliest forerunner of boy band music began in the late 19th century as a cappella barbershop quartets . [SEP] when did they become popular ? [SEP] the term boy band was not established until the late 1980s as before that they were called male vocal groups or " hep harmony singing groups " . [SEP] who was the first major boy band group ?
boy band [SEP] early history [SEP] when was the first boy band ? [SEP] the earliest forerunner of boy band music began in the late 19th century as a cappella barbershop quartets . [SEP] when did they become popular ? [SEP] the term boy band was not established until the late 1980s as before that they were called male vocal groups or " hep harmony singing groups " . [SEP] who was the first major boy band group ? [SEP] the liverpool quartet known as the beatles were not only the quintessential rock band , [SEP] what were some other early boy bands ?
boy band [SEP] early history [SEP] when was the first boy band ? [SEP] the earliest forerunner of boy band music began in the late 19th century as a cappella barbershop quartets . [SEP] when did they become popular ? [SEP] the term boy band was not established until the late 1980s as before that they were called male vocal groups or " hep harmony singing groups " . [SEP] who was the first major boy band group ? [SEP] the liverpool quartet known as the beatles were not only the quintessential rock band , [SEP] what were some other early boy bands ? melungeon [SEP] origins [SEP] what was their origin ? [SEP] children were assigned the social status and ethnicity of their mother , regardless of their father 's ethnicity or citizenship . [SEP] they migrated together from western virginia through the piedmont frontier of north carolina , before settling primarily in the mountains of east tennessee . linus pauling [SEP] political criticism [SEP] what types of things was he criticized for ? linus pauling [SEP] political criticism [SEP] what types of things was he criticized for ? [SEP] peace activism , his frequent travels , and his enthusiastic expansion into chemical - biomedical research all aroused opposition at caltech . [SEP] who opposed his works ? [SEP] scientists who appreciated the contributions that he had made in chemistry , disagreed with his political positions and saw him as a naive spokesman for soviet communism . [SEP] what political positions made him unpopular ? [SEP] pauling was referred to not only as a collaborator , but as a " fellow traveler " of proponents of soviet - style communism . [SEP] is there anything else unique about his political beliefs ?

linus pauling [SEP] political criticism [SEP] what types of things was he criticized for ? [SEP] peace activism , his frequent travels , and his enthusiastic expansion into chemical - biomedical research all aroused opposition at caltech . [SEP] who opposed his works ? [SEP] scientists who appreciated the contributions that he had made in chemistry , disagreed with his political positions and saw him as a naive spokesman for soviet communism . [SEP] is there anything else unique about his political beliefs ? [SEP] in 1960 he was ordered to appear before the senate internal security subcommittee , [SEP] were there any consequences for him ? [SEP] pauling sued the magazine , its publisher william rusher , and its editor william f. buckley , jr for $ 1 million . he lost both his libel suits and the 1968 appeal . winnie madikizela - mandela [SEP] apartheid : 1963 - 1985 [SEP] what happened during apartheid ? winnie madikizela - mandela [SEP] apartheid : 1963 - 1985 [SEP] what happened during apartheid ? [SEP] winnie was regularly detained by the national party government . she was tortured , subjected to house arrest , kept under surveillance , held in solitary confinement for over a year and [SEP] and what else ? [SEP] and even banished to a remote town . she emerged as a leading opponent of apartheid during the later years of her husband 's imprisonment [SEP] what did she do to fight apartheid ? [SEP] ) . for many of those years , she was banished to the town of brandfort in the orange free state and confined to the area , except [SEP] except what happened ? [SEP] except for when she was allowed to visit her husband at robben island . beginning in 1969 , she spent eighteen months in solitary confinement at pretoria central prison . [SEP] why did she go to prison ?
winnie madikizela - mandela [SEP] apartheid : 1963 - 1985 [SEP] what happened during apartheid ? [SEP] winnie was regularly detained by the national party government . she was tortured , subjected to house arrest , kept under surveillance , held in solitary confinement for over a year and [SEP] and what else ? [SEP] and even banished to a remote town . she emerged as a leading opponent of apartheid during the later years of her husband 's imprisonment [SEP] what did she do to fight apartheid ? [SEP] ) . for many of those years , she was banished to the town of brandfort in the orange free state and confined to the area , except [SEP] except what happened ? [SEP] except for when she was allowed to visit her husband at robben island . beginning in 1969 , she spent eighteen months in solitary confinement at pretoria central prison . [SEP] why did she go to prison ? [SEP] due to her political activities , winnie was regularly detained by the national party government . [SEP] how was she involved in politics ?
winnie madikizela - mandela [SEP] apartheid : 1963 - 1985 [SEP] what happened during apartheid ? [SEP] winnie was regularly detained by the national party government . she was tortured , subjected to house arrest , kept under surveillance , held in solitary confinement for over a year and [SEP] and what else ? [SEP] and even banished to a remote town . she emerged as a leading opponent of apartheid during the later years of her husband 's imprisonment [SEP] what did she do to fight apartheid ? [SEP] ) . for many of those years , she was banished to the town of brandfort in the orange free state and confined to the area , except [SEP] except what happened ? [SEP] except for when she was allowed to visit her husband at robben island . beginning in 1969 , she spent eighteen months in solitary confinement at pretoria central prison . [SEP] why did she go to prison ? [SEP] due to her political activities , winnie was regularly detained by the national party government . [SEP] how was she involved in politics ? [SEP] she organised local clinics , campaigned actively for equal rights and was promoted by the anc as a symbol of their struggle against apartheid . [SEP] did she get involved in any other ways ?
winnie madikizela - mandela [SEP] apartheid : 1963 - 1985 [SEP] what happened during apartheid ? [SEP] winnie was regularly detained by the national party government . she was tortured , subjected to house arrest , kept under surveillance , held in solitary confinement for over a year and [SEP] and what else ? [SEP] and even banished to a remote town . she emerged as a leading opponent of apartheid during the later years of her husband 's imprisonment [SEP] what did she do to fight apartheid ? [SEP] ) . for many of those years , she was banished to the town of brandfort in the orange free state and confined to the area , except [SEP] except what happened ? [SEP] except for when she was allowed to visit her husband at robben island . beginning in 1969 , she spent eighteen months in solitary confinement at pretoria central prison . [SEP] why did she go to prison ? [SEP] due to her political activities , winnie was regularly detained by the national party government . [SEP] how was she involved in politics ? [SEP] she organised local clinics , campaigned actively for equal rights and was promoted by the anc as a symbol of their struggle against apartheid . [SEP] did she get involved in any other ways ? [SEP] beginning in 1969 , she spent eighteen months in solitary confinement at pretoria central prison . it was at this time that winnie mandela became well known in the western world . [SEP] are there any other interesting aspects about this article ?
winnie madikizela - mandela [SEP] apartheid : 1963 - 1985 [SEP] what happened during apartheid ? [SEP] winnie was regularly detained by the national party government . she was tortured , subjected to house arrest , kept under surveillance , held in solitary confinement for over a year and [SEP] and what else ? [SEP] and even banished to a remote town . she emerged as a leading opponent of apartheid during the later years of her husband 's imprisonment [SEP] what did she do to fight apartheid ? [SEP] except for when she was allowed to visit her husband at robben island . beginning in 1969 , she spent eighteen months in solitary confinement at pretoria central prison . burlesque [SEP] literary origins and development [SEP] where did the name burlesque come from ? [SEP] the word first appears in a title in francesco berni 's opere burlesche of the early 16th century , [SEP] when did burlesque come about ? [SEP] for a time , burlesque verses were known as poesie bernesca in his honour . ' burlesque ' as a literary term became widespread in 17th century italy and france , [SEP] are there any other interesting aspects about this article ? [SEP] shakespeare 's pyramus and thisbe scene in midsummer night 's dream and the general mocking of romance in beaumont and fletcher 's [SEP] what started the development of burlesque ?
burlesque [SEP] literary origins and development [SEP] where did the name burlesque come from ? [SEP] the word first appears in a title in francesco berni 's opere burlesche of the early 16th century , [SEP] when did burlesque come about ? ' burlesque ' as a literary term became widespread in 17th century italy and france , [SEP] are there any other interesting aspects about this article ? [SEP] in 17th century spain , playwright and poet miguel de cervantes ridiculed medieval romance in his many satirical works . [SEP] what was the first performance of burlesque ?
burlesque [SEP] literary origins and development [SEP] where did the name burlesque come from ? [SEP] the word first appears in a title in francesco berni 's opere burlesche of the early 16th century , [SEP] when did burlesque come about ? [SEP] for a time , burlesque verses were known as poesie bernesca in his honour . ' burlesque ' as a literary term became widespread in 17th century italy and france , [SEP] are there any other interesting aspects about this article ? [SEP] shakespeare 's pyramus and thisbe scene in midsummer night 's dream and the general mocking of romance in beaumont and fletcher 's [SEP] what started the development of burlesque ? [SEP] in 17th century spain , playwright and poet miguel de cervantes ridiculed medieval romance in his many satirical works . [SEP] what was the first performance of burlesque ? [SEP] the general mocking of romance in beaumont and fletcher 's the knight of the burning pestle were early examples of such imitation . [SEP] did burlesque stay true to its original development or were there changes ?

[SEP] the general mocking of romance in beaumont and fletcher 's the knight of the burning pestle were early examples of such imitation . [SEP] did burlesque stay true to its original development or were there changes ? joshua chamberlain [SEP] battle of gettysburg [SEP] why was chamberlin known for this [SEP] chamberlain became most famous for his achievements during the battle of gettysburg . [SEP] " he taught that all can be saved equally , without regard to caste , through devotion ( bhakti ) to vithoba " [SEP] were his writings taken seriously ? [SEP] he greatly influenced groups of people who were forbidden by the brahmin elite from studying the vedas , such as women and members of the shudra and untouchable communities .
